<highlight>
<T1>sprinter tyson gay received a one-year ban from usada for a doping violation and forfeited his 2012 olympic silver medal.</T1>

<T1.1>gay tested positive for a banned anabolic steroid at the u.s. championships on june 23, 2013.</T1.1>
<T1.1.1>his suspension takes effect from that date, making him eligible to compete later in the summer.</T1.1.1>
<T1.1.2>he admitted to using a product containing a banned substance.</T1.1.2>

<T1.2>gay received a shortened suspension for cooperating with investigators.</T1.2>
<T1.2.1>the standard ban for a doping violation is two years.</T1.2.1>
<T1.2.2>usada ceo travis tygart praised gay for accepting responsibility and cooperating fully.</T1.2.2>
<T1.2.3>the suspension length is subject to appeal by the iaaf and wada.</T1.2.3>

<T1.3>gay forfeited all results and prizes dating back to july 15, 2012.</T1.3>
<T1.3.1>this includes his silver medal from the men's 4x100m relay at the 2012 london olympics.</T1.3.1>
<T1.3.2>the ioc stated it was satisfied with the punishment and supports clean athletes.</T1.3.2>

<T1.4>gay is a highly accomplished sprinter with notable career achievements.</T1.4>
<T1.4.1>he is the joint second fastest man over 100 meters in history with a time of 9.69 seconds.</T1.4.1>
<T1.4.2>he won gold in the 100 meters, 200 meters, and 4x100m relay at the 2007 world championships.</T1.4.2>
<T1.4.3>he has been a main rival of usain bolt over the past few years.</T1.4.3>

<T1.5>the news of gay's ban came alongside a similar doping case involving former world record holder asafa powell.</T1.5>
<T1.5.1>jamaica's asafa powell received an 18-month ban for his doping offense.</T1.5.1>
<T1.5.2>the concurrent announcements shocked followers of track and field.</T1.5.2>
</highlight>